WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
[Amit Varma]: This episode of The Seen and The Unseen is brought to you by Intel.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Two roads diverged in a wood and you, you took the one you're passing through.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Why do we take the paths we take in our lives?

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.000
[Amit Varma]: For some of us, it's social convention and inertia.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:24.000
[Amit Varma]: When I was growing up in the 1980s, good middle class boys were supposed to be engineers and doctors.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And maybe do that newfangled thing an MBA, certainly try for UPSC.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Why not just go along?

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Some of us manage to ignore these conventions and find that golden intersection between doing something we love,

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.000
[Amit Varma]: something we are good at and something we can get paid for.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
[Amit Varma]: But whatever choice we make, there's usually some rationale behind it.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Maybe a steady career, maybe a pot of gold if we get to the end of the rainbow,

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
[Amit Varma]: maybe an artistic satisfaction that can't be measured only in banknotes.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:58.000
[Amit Varma]: But some people, they go against the tide and make choices that seem destined not to work.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
[Amit Varma]: Your enemies laugh at you, your friends feel sorry for you.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:03.000
[Amit Varma]: But you gotta do what you gotta do.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
[Amit Varma]: As a great Kashi Nath Singh wrote in Kashi Ka Assi,

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Bhaar mein jaye duniya, hum bajaye harmoniya.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen,

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
[Unknown]: our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Let the world go to hell, I will play my harmonium.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Abhinandan Sekri, the founder and CEO of News Laundry.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Abhinandan joined the news industry as a journalist with NewsTrack,

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.000
[Amit Varma]: a video news magazine that circulated by videocassette long before the internet existed.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
[Amit Varma]: His career took many unconventional routes after that.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
[Amit Varma]: He was an assistant director on Meera Nair's film, Monsoon Wedding.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.000
[Amit Varma]: He jumped into making travel shows for television when there was no market for travel shows on television.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
[Amit Varma]: He started an NGO with Arvind Kejriwal and Manish Sisodia, among others,

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
[Amit Varma]: at a time when they were all unknown and such activism seemed doomed to failure.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
[Amit Varma]: He wrote comedy for television while the world went to hell around him.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
[Amit Varma]: And eventually, he formed News Laundry, a media house with a difference.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:14.000
[Amit Varma]: They would ignore advertisers and subsist directly of the goodwill of their readers.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
[Amit Varma]: Today, everyone is talking about this as a new trend in the creator economy.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Abhinandan and his team have been doing this for a decade.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:27.000
[Amit Varma]: When I invited him on the show and he agreed, I didn't have to do much digging about what kind of person he is.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:31.000
[Amit Varma]: One thing I love about Abhinandan is that what you see is what you get.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:35.000
[Amit Varma]: His public persona has no filters. I love that about him.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Before recording this episode, we were chatting about Aakar Patel's delightful tweets

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:45.000
[Amit Varma]: and I pointed out that Aakar has become a personification of the phrase, no more fucks to give.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.000
[Amit Varma]: Aakar is fearless in a way that most of us can only admire from a distance.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
[Amit Varma]: I felt Abhinandan had reached that state as well.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.000
[Amit Varma]: But he told me, nope, he still has some way to go.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Be that as it may, he is a fearless crusader for a better India.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And in times when the rest of the media seems to have sold itself out,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
[Amit Varma]: News Laundry continues to speak truth to power.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Many of us admire this, but we should also put our money where our mouth is.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
[Amit Varma]: If you agree, head on over to newslaundry.com slash subscription and support News Laundry.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
[Amit Varma]: You can even get a 25% discount if you write to Abhinandan at an email ID he reveals at the end of the show.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:26.000
[Amit Varma]: But I would say, ignore the discount, pay the full price. Pay to keep news free.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Now if that sounds like a commercial, it isn't. The commercial comes now.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.000
[Amit Varma]: How secure are we?

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
[Amit Varma]: In general, we are not as secure as we think.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:41.000
[Amit Varma]: We rely on the state for the rule of law, but across the world, states tend to be predators rather than protectors.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
[Amit Varma]: We do get some security that comes from social trust and conventions, but that can work both ways.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
[Amit Varma]: One place where we are relatively secure though is the internet.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
[Amit Varma]: I often speak of technology with hope, as it empowers individuals and it also protects them.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And it does it so well and in such an unseen way that we often take it for granted.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:06.000
[Amit Varma]: There is no better example of this than the sponsor of this episode, Intel.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Devices powered by Intel help businesses stay connected and secure and provide them performance and stability.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:18.000
[Amit Varma]: Intel's 11th Gen vPro platform has layers of security that go beyond software,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
[Amit Varma]: with advanced threat detection and comprehensive multi-level security features.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
[Amit Varma]: No one will mess with you if you have Intel by your side.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.000
[Amit Varma]: The Intel vPro platform, built for business, wherever business happens.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Abhinandan, welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.000
[Guest]: Thank you, Amit. Pleasure to be here.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:44.000
[Amit Varma]: So it's interesting, you know, I realized while looking up your bare biographical details that we are the same age.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
[Amit Varma]: You're both 47, though I'll get to 48 before you, so I'll be a step ahead.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And although we have sort of had orthogonal careers in the media, in journalism and all of that,

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:00.000
[Amit Varma]: I actually don't know much about you and I'm not even sure how much we really have in common,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
[Amit Varma]: even though we've almost had, you know, parallel lives in Delhi and Bombay.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
[Amit Varma]: I was in Delhi for a very brief while.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
[Amit Varma]: I was in Bombay for a very brief while.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.000
[Amit Varma]: There you go, yeah.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And I've also worked in television and I've also been a journalist and we both do podcasts, all of that.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
[Amit Varma]: So I want to know a little bit more about the non-public persona.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Like if somebody searches for your name, you're all over.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of the delightful things that I kind of like about everything I've seen of yours and whatever,

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:32.000
[Amit Varma]: is that what you see is what you get, you know, you're just putting yourself out there.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:37.000
[Amit Varma]: So one gets a sense that there is a public persona of Abhinandan Sekri and hey, everybody knows that.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure a lot of people must have told you that they feel a sense of familiarity with you when they meet you

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
[Amit Varma]: because they're so used to watching you.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
[Amit Varma]: But take me before that, like, you know, where did you grow up?

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:47.000
[Amit Varma]: What was your childhood like?

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
[Amit Varma]: What kind of a boy were you?

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.000
[Guest]: Well, I've been through, let's say, two distinct phases as a boy.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
[Guest]: I had a very idyllic small town childhood.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
[Guest]: You know, Malguri days of the North, kind of.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
[Guest]: Dehradun was a small town, small town where everybody walked.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: The only time your car came out was if you're going to the club, you know, one of those evenings.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:13.000
[Guest]: My dad was a fauji, my mother was a school teacher.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:20.000
[Guest]: And Dehradun was a town for retired people and faujis and teachers and schools.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
[Guest]: And I'm talking like the 70s and 80s.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:25.000
[Guest]: So there weren't as many schools as there are now.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:32.000
[Guest]: Like, there was like, there were no red lights in Dehradun till like, even the late 90s.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
[Guest]: It's just after Uttarakhand was made and became a capital, it became anything.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:41.000
[Guest]: So, and when dad was in the army, you know, before he took premature retirement,

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:47.000
[Guest]: because mum was a teacher in Vellum Girls School, we were allowed to be educated at the Doon School.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.000
[Guest]: So it was like a quota, kind of.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:55.000
[Guest]: So especially when many people who are, who like me, have got the benefit of quota,

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
[Guest]: I don't realize we are quota kids.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Guest]: And when they grow up and they're doing really well, they say, bloody, what is this quota?

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
[Guest]: I was like, can I use F words here on your show?

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:04.000
[Unknown]: Of course, please.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
[Unknown]: I was like, fuck you, you're a quota kid.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.000
[Guest]: You would have been nothing had it not been for a quota.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:16.000
[Guest]: So, you know, I went to Vellum Boys School from class 1 to 6 and then Doon 7 to 12.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
[Guest]: And in fact, my grandfather used to teach Tamil and English at Doon.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
[Guest]: That's much before I was born.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.000
[Guest]: So our family has been in Dehradun for a long time.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
[Guest]: Mother is a Tamilian and father is a Punjabi.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:28.000
[Guest]: But during the holidays, my dad was in the army.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
[Guest]: So he was posted to, you know, Siliguri, Bhopal, Mathura.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
[Guest]: We spent a lot of time in cantonments, which meant air rifles.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
[Guest]: And now when I think of it, maybe that's how we've turned out so screwed up.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
[Guest]: Like, I would never let my nephew go with an air gun to shoot squirrels and chameleons and birds.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
[Guest]: But that's what we did, you know, because cantonments are safe.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.000
[Guest]: The rule was you had to get back home when lights are on.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:54.000
[Guest]: So you'd go into the bushes, you'd go into the thicket, you'd catch, you know,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:59.000
[Guest]: in little Rasna bottles, we'd catch tadpoles and then watch them grow.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:05.000
[Guest]: In Hajmola bottles, catch caterpillars, watch them become pupas and then butterflies.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:07.000
[Guest]: And even Dehradun was like that.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.000
[Guest]: You could go in. There was no fear.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:14.000
[Guest]: Like from the time I was six or seven, I could walk anywhere I wanted.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
[Guest]: My folks weren't worried.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
[Guest]: So yeah, it was an idyllic childhood.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
[Guest]: And school was, you know, although I was a day scholar till I was in class nine,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
[Guest]: because I was allowed to be all the both well and do all boarding.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.000
[Guest]: Because my mother was a teacher, I was allowed to go back home in the evening.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
[Guest]: So it was fun.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:43.000
[Guest]: I was a kind of, I won't say I was shy, but I was a quieter kid till I was maybe 12 or 13.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:47.000
[Guest]: After which I became an aggressive boy.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.000
[Guest]: I was very tiny. I was much smaller than all my batchmates.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
[Guest]: I was like, you know, way, way smaller.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:57.000
[Guest]: So I guess you compensate for that by being extremely aggressive.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:00.000
[Guest]: Because you know, boarding school, it's like prison rules.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
[Guest]: You know, if you don't push back, you.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
[Guest]: So you have to compensate for size.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
[Guest]: If, you know, if you fuck with me, I'm going to give you such a tongue lashing

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
[Guest]: and humiliate you in front of everybody.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
[Guest]: So that's how you get a bit aggressive.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:20.000
[Guest]: So now when I look back, I, you know, I'd like to not have been that aggressive

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
[Guest]: when I was in my teens.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:23.000
[Guest]: But those are the two.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
[Guest]: But yeah, before that, I was very quiet and retiring.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
[Guest]: I have two older sisters.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
[Guest]: So in any case, I was used to being quiet.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
[Guest]: One is six years older, one is three years older.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:40.000
[Guest]: And there was, you know, kite flying, going for those Jhankis of Ramlila,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:43.000
[Guest]: watching the Ravan thing from the club.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.000
[Guest]: And you were the youngest because all my sister's friends are much older than me.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
[Guest]: So you, you were the sidekick who ran behind the gang.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest]: No one really was looking out for you.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest]: So it was a good, I'd say it was a very peaceful, happy childhood.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I've seen pictures on your Instagram of your school years,

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.000
[Amit Varma]: I think where, you know, there's one picture of a group of you

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
[Amit Varma]: and someone makes a comment about which one is you.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:08.000
[Amit Varma]: But I could make out you're kind of in the center.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
[Amit Varma]: You're the same kind of face.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And there's another one where there are, you know, one, two, three,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
[Amit Varma]: it's like a vertical picture, people leaning on each other

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
[Amit Varma]: and you're the kid at the bottom.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you mentioned sort of like one of the things

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.000
[Amit Varma]: that I remember not just having in school,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
[Amit Varma]: but kind of for much longer.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think people have it throughout their lives.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:29.000
[Amit Varma]: It's sort of the anxiety of fitting in, you know,

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:33.000
[Amit Varma]: where you're still kind of discovering who you are in a sense,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
[Amit Varma]: as if that process is ever complete.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.000
[Amit Varma]: But that's sort of a dominant anxiety for many people.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
[Amit Varma]: At one level, the anxiety of fitting in.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
[Amit Varma]: At another level, the anxiety of what people will think of you,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
[Amit Varma]: which drives sometimes the things that you do,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
[Unknown]: the music you listen to and the music you pretend to listen to,

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
[Amit Varma]: the books you carry around and the books you really enjoy reading

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of these things about myself,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
[Amit Varma]: I realized only later through looking back,

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.000
[Amit Varma]: through self-reflection and all of that.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And it seems you've also kind of done a little bit of that

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.000
[Amit Varma]: because you just use the phrase now when I look back, you know.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about, you know,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
[Amit Varma]: when you look back at the young Abhinandan,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
[Amit Varma]: what were those anxieties?

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:15.000
[Amit Varma]: When did you lose those anxieties?

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:18.000
[Amit Varma]: Where does that process come if it is complete?

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think it's complete for you.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think I kind of took a long time to get there.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:27.000
[Amit Varma]: But where does it happen where you get comfortable in your own skin?

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:32.000
[Guest]: I mean, I would say there wasn't a time, like it wasn't an event.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:37.000
[Guest]: It's more a process like the pupa turning into a butterfly kind of thing.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:42.000
[Guest]: But yeah, I'd say maybe late 20s, early 30s onwards,

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:49.000
[Guest]: I was, you know, pretty sure of my confidence levels were solid.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
[Guest]: It wasn't a put on confidence which you have when you're in your 20s.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
[Guest]: Like you said, what is expected of you is like,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
[Guest]: and I was always confident.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
[Guest]: And I'll get into the reason why that is,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
[Guest]: you know, when we get into this a little bit.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
[Guest]: But the real confidence, I guess, only in your 30s

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
[Guest]: is when it kind of starts to develop.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
[Guest]: Stuff like I love Punjabi music, right?

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.000
[Guest]: So if I was going to pick up a girl or, you know,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
[Guest]: I would switch to English music, you know,

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
[Guest]: right up to your late 20s or 30s.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.000
[Guest]: Now I don't give a shit.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
[Guest]: I was like, fuck, I listen to Geeta Zelda.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
[Unknown]: You want to sit, sit. You don't sit, don't sit.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:27.000
[Guest]: So those kind of things, you know, take a little longer.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:30.000
[Guest]: But I mean, yeah, that's when it happened.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
[Guest]: And I think Delhi has a lot to do with it, you know,

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
[Guest]: because when I was young, when you talk about the anxieties,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
[Guest]: one is, of course, your middle class.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
[Guest]: And, you know, the way middle class is used is,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
[Guest]: let's face it, I was privileged even though

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
[Guest]: I was not a Nikhil Nanda or Jyotirath Dasindhya,

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.000
[Guest]: but I was still more privileged than 90% of the country.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
[Guest]: But because our society has been so, you know,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
[Guest]: segmented that you're the bottom of the top.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.000
[Guest]: So stuff like not being able to afford the shoes

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
[Guest]: that others could, you know, not be able to afford a Nike,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
[Guest]: you wear power, it, you know,

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
[Guest]: it kind of bites you a little self-conscious about it.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.000
[Guest]: But luckily it was never a big thing for me because my folks,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
[Guest]: I mean, that was a new thing of what brand I was wearing

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
[Guest]: only when I, you know, in my teens.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
[Guest]: Before that, because of the kind of people my parents are,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
[Guest]: I was never even aware that there was anything

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
[Guest]: other than what we have.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
[Guest]: One is because there was no cable TV.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
[Guest]: So you didn't know.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
[Guest]: B, that wasn't a priority in our house.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
[Guest]: So you didn't know anyway.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
[Guest]: And there was never any shame.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
[Guest]: Like my mother comes from a family of, you know,

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.000
[Guest]: teachers and academics, like my aunts have been teachers,

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.000
[Guest]: my mother's a teacher, my grandfather's a teacher.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
[Guest]: And, you know, there was a typical Tamilians

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
[Guest]: who really chatto a lot of books.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
[Guest]: We had a lot of books at home.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
[Guest]: Like we had more books than anything else, basically.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
[Guest]: You may have a broken sofa, but your books are, you know,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:01.000
[Guest]: kept well.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
[Guest]: So there was never really that need.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.000
[Guest]: But I did go through a phase, I'd say in my teens to college,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
[Guest]: where you weren't, you were aware that you don't have

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.000
[Guest]: as much as the other kids who you grew up with.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.000
[Guest]: But honestly, it did not impact me as much as it impacted

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
[Guest]: others around that I saw, you know, because there were

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
[Guest]: a lot of us who were service kids and a lot of us

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
[Guest]: who were, you know, very wealthy.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
[Guest]: So it did impact me a little bit, but not enough

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
[Guest]: for it to take a knock on my confidence.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
[Guest]: I would be self-conscious about it and sometimes

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:34.000
[Guest]: a little embarrassed, but not enough to not speak out.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:38.000
[Guest]: So, yeah, and I think for that, you know,

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:41.000
[Guest]: my mom and my sisters are, and I do think,

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
[Guest]: I'm not married and I don't have kids,

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
[Guest]: but it's funny coming from me.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:51.000
[Guest]: I think the unit of family, I mean, for all my progressive

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:57.000
[Guest]: and, you know, bohemian choices and angles in life,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Guest]: from my experience, I'll say, if you have a solid family,

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.000
[Guest]: you can be so fucking confident that no one can shake that confidence.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
[Guest]: Because no matter what I did, for my mother,

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
[Guest]: I was always a star.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
[Guest]: You know, I'm always the star.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:12.000
[Guest]: Even now she says, you know,

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.000
[Guest]: internet pe kuch chalata hoga type, you know, she's,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
[Guest]: but, and I have two older sisters,

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
[Guest]: they're both really smart, bright, very independent.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.000
[Guest]: So confidence was something that I saw and learned.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.000
[Guest]: So, yeah, so I was conscious that I'm not as well off

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.000
[Guest]: as many of the kids I'm growing up with,

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:34.000
[Guest]: but, and sometimes I was embarrassed because,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
[Guest]: like your car doesn't have an AC, your car may break down.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
[Guest]: I have a secondhand Fiat, which is like 40,000 rupees.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.000
[Guest]: And at that time, you know, Maruti 800s had just come out.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:45.000
[Guest]: So people had Maruti 800s, some who were very rich had Mercedes.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:46.000
[Guest]: And you're going for a, you know,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
[Guest]: a friend's party who lives in this big bungalow

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
[Guest]: in North Delhi somewhere, and, you know,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
[Guest]: his probably one wheel of his car is worth your car.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
[Guest]: So that, you know, you, but otherwise, you know,

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
[Guest]: me and another friend of mine were both service background.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
[Guest]: So we'd always say, you know,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
[Guest]: our dads couldn't give us a BMW, but give us a car.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
[Guest]: You know, that's, even if it didn't work half the time,

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Guest]: which is more than what a lot of others get, but yeah.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:11.000
[Guest]: So, I mean, that kind of,

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
[Guest]: it vanished early enough for me for it to,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
[Guest]: and even today money is not a motivation in my life.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
[Guest]: I want to, you know, fairly comfortable life.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
[Guest]: And I want choices, but I read, I mean,

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
[Guest]: I, you see how I dress, you know,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
[Guest]: my entire wardrobe must be worth 20,000 rupees.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
[Guest]: I don't give a fuck about that shit.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
[Guest]: That's never been an issue, but it was when I was young.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:36.000
[Guest]: I tell, you know, many of my younger peers this,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
[Guest]: that when I wanted to buy expensive stuff,

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
[Guest]: I couldn't afford it.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
[Guest]: So basically God outwits you.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:47.000
[Guest]: He gives you what you want, but not when you want it.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
[Guest]: And when he gives it to you, you don't want it.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
[Guest]: So I was very, you know, keen to buy, you know,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
[Guest]: shoes, kids that were expensive, you know,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
[Guest]: back then Air Jordans and shit, you couldn't,

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
[Guest]: I couldn't afford them.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:16:59.000
[Guest]: Now I may not be able to buy a Rolls,

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
[Guest]: but I can buy any shoe I want,

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
[Guest]: but I don't have anything other than juttis

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:05.000
[Guest]: and you know, my one pair of kids.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
[Guest]: I used to love the Harley Davidson boots

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:08.000
[Guest]: because I'd seen friends of mine wear it.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
[Guest]: And a pair of Harley Davidson boots at that time

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
[Guest]: was like 8,000, 7,000, I'm talking like nineties, man.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
[Guest]: That was like, when I was a new strike,

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.000
[Guest]: my salary was three and a half thousand bucks.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
[Guest]: So when you can afford it,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:23.000
[Guest]: you just want Kolhapuri chappals and kurta pyjamas.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
[Amit Varma]: So, so yeah.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, maybe the mindset of not wanting things

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
[Amit Varma]: is also a kind of richness.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:33.000
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned the books that surrounded you in your house

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
[Amit Varma]: and you know how it didn't matter

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
[Amit Varma]: if the sofa was broken, the books were all around.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And my childhood was similar to that,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
[Amit Varma]: extremely privileged.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:41.000
[Amit Varma]: My dad was a civil servant,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
[Amit Varma]: surrounded by books all the time.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's what I remember.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
[Amit Varma]: So my dad passed away earlier this year

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:47.000
[Amit Varma]: and we just sold his house

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
[Amit Varma]: and I have to go there next month

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
[Guest]: to clear out some of the stuff.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
[Amit Varma]: This is in Chandigarh.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And the thing that I think about most is books

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.000
[Amit Varma]: because all those books

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
[Amit Varma]: and I've got to find someone to give it away

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
[Amit Varma]: to some library or charity or whatever.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And all those books in a sense are my nursery.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:05.000
[Amit Varma]: They are kind of what shaped me

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.000
[Amit Varma]: because as a kid, I just sort of grew up

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:09.000
[Amit Varma]: just reading all the time

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
[Amit Varma]: and in different ways,

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of forming my imaginative world there

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
[Amit Varma]: and kind of starting from there.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:16.000
[Amit Varma]: What was it like for you?

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Because you mentioned your mother was also an academic.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Her whole side of the family was academics.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
[Amit Varma]: They were all obviously into reading.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Reading must have been both something sacred

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:29.000
[Amit Varma]: and at the same time a source of great pleasure

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Amit Varma]: for all of you.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:31.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:32.000
[Amit Varma]: what kind of stuff you read.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course we had a limited variety of books

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.000
[Amit Varma]: in general available.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
[Amit Varma]: So kids would grow up reading the same thing,

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
[Amit Varma]: even the serious reading they would progress to

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:41.000
[Amit Varma]: would be, you know,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure there are lots of commonalities,

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
[Amit Varma]: but give me a sense of how that was shaping you.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
[Guest]: A lot of what you read at that time

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:49.000
[Guest]: was because you heard your mother say,

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.000
[Guest]: oh, this is very good.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
[Guest]: So you read it and you didn't really have a view

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:53.000
[Guest]: of what's good or bad.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:54.000
[Guest]: You just read.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
[Guest]: So my mother had this big collection,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
[Guest]: she still does, of P.G. Woodhouse

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
[Unknown]: and Jeeves and all that.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
[Guest]: So you went through those

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
[Guest]: before you really could understand them.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:05.000
[Guest]: Like now when I think back,

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:06.000
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think, you know,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Guest]: 13, 14-year-olds should be reading this,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
[Guest]: especially someone who has no insight

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
[Guest]: or idea of British humor or British life

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:13.000
[Guest]: or British society.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:14.000
[Guest]: There's a lot of that subtext

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
[Guest]: and that's the world it's in.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.000
[Guest]: But you read it because you heard your mother say,

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
[Guest]: oh, how fine, haha, innit?

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:23.000
[Guest]: So you read it.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
[Guest]: The other thing that my folks had

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
[Guest]: was they had all the reader's digests

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.000
[Guest]: because they used to subscribe

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
[Guest]: from like 72 onwards.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:31.000
[Guest]: They were all...

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:35.000
[Guest]: So I got operated for appendicitis

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
[Guest]: when I was in class eight.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:38.000
[Guest]: So I had to, you know,

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.000
[Guest]: be in bed for about 10, 12 days.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
[Guest]: And during that time,

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.000
[Guest]: I chartered, like,

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
[Guest]: I think from 72, 73 onwards,

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
[Guest]: all the reader's digests.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:49.000
[Guest]: So, you know,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
[Guest]: whether it's that drama in real life...

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:52.000
[Unknown]: Humor in uniform.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:53.000
[Unknown]: Humor in uniform,

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:54.000
[Guest]: college humor,

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
[Guest]: laughter, the best medicine.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:57.000
[Guest]: And of course,

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:58.000
[Guest]: there was drama in real life

00:19:58.000 --> 00:19:59.000
[Guest]: and there used to be this,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
[Guest]: you know, the long walk home type.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:02.000
[Guest]: Later I got to know

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:03.000
[Guest]: there was a certain Christian angle

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.000
[Guest]: to the reader's digest.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:05.000
[Guest]: So all these stories

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:06.000
[Guest]: had a certain message

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
[Guest]: about there being a God

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:09.000
[Guest]: and you should be good.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:10.000
[Guest]: And it was subliminal.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:11.000
[Guest]: Of course, it didn't

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:12.000
[Guest]: convert you to Christianity

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:13.000
[Guest]: in case everyone wants to go

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.000
[Guest]: and, you know, attack the reader's digest.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
[Guest]: But later I understood

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:18.000
[Guest]: that there was a certain politics

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:19.000
[Guest]: behind that as well.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:21.000
[Guest]: But I charted all that.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:22.000
[Guest]: Then you try to pick up stuff

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:23.000
[Guest]: that is way beyond your league,

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
[Guest]: like War and Peace

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:26.000
[Guest]: and Thorn Birds,

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:27.000
[Guest]: which used to be this thick book.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Colin McAloo, I remember that.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:30.000
[Guest]: So, you know,

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:31.000
[Guest]: you pick those up,

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:32.000
[Guest]: you abandon those halfway,

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:33.000
[Guest]: but you learn something.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.000
[Guest]: You learn English words.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
[Guest]: Then there was a lot of Thomas Hardy,

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:39.000
[Guest]: which I would still recommend,

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:40.000
[Guest]: that, you know,

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:41.000
[Guest]: I mean, I wouldn't recommend it

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:42.000
[Guest]: to someone your in my age

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:43.000
[Guest]: because there's a certain,

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
[Guest]: you know, I don't mean Tess

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:46.000
[Guest]: and Jude the Obscure,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:47.000
[Guest]: which are very depressing,

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:48.000
[Guest]: but, you know,

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:49.000
[Guest]: Return of the Native

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
[Guest]: or Far From the Madding Crowd.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.000
[Guest]: There's a certain Yash Chopra-esque-ness

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:54.000
[Guest]: to his books.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.000
[Guest]: There's the hero

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:56.000
[Guest]: and there's the Evelyn Bathsheba.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:57.000
[Guest]: She's vain.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:58.000
[Guest]: And then, you know,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:20:59.000
[Guest]: she falls in love with someone

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:00.000
[Guest]: and then, you know,

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:01.000
[Guest]: the other guy comes

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.000
[Guest]: and, you know, saves her

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
[Guest]: and then there's some tragedy.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:05.000
[Guest]: So, I mean,

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:06.000
[Guest]: I think Thomas Hardy was,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:07.000
[Guest]: you know,

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:08.000
[Guest]: the thinking man,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:09.000
[Guest]: Yash Chopra.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:10.000
[Guest]: So, you know,

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.000
[Guest]: those kind of books were there.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
[Guest]: So those you appreciated

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:14.000
[Guest]: at a younger age.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:15.000
[Guest]: And I still would recommend them

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:16.000
[Guest]: to people who are young

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:17.000
[Guest]: because I think there's a lot,

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:18.000
[Guest]: I mean, there's something,

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:19.000
[Guest]: there's a feel-good factor.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:20.000
[Guest]: You learn something,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:21.000
[Guest]: he writes well,

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:23.000
[Guest]: it's a story well told.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:24.000
[Guest]: Then, of course,

