[Guest]: Why would you come here if that was your intention? But most importantly, opinions will not for

03:34:30.560 --> 03:34:37.520
[Guest]: what I'm doing. It has to be ground reports. The crux of growth is ground reports. First

03:34:37.520 --> 03:34:41.920
[Guest]: post had more opinion piece than anybody does. They will know it's going to pay to pay first

03:34:41.920 --> 03:34:47.360
[Guest]: post. Nobody. Your ground reporting has to be of a certain caliber. If it has to grow

03:34:47.360 --> 03:34:52.160
[Guest]: and podcasts are very important because podcasts are very important for your primary tribe.

03:34:52.160 --> 03:35:00.440
[Guest]: Your primary tribe likes the sound of your message of your passion. But podcasts are

03:35:00.440 --> 03:35:04.960
[Guest]: high engagement. Absolutely. So that and we started podcasts, you know, before anybody

03:35:04.960 --> 03:35:11.560
[Guest]: had because I was addicted to podcast from the mid 2000s. So I was just addicted to the

03:35:11.560 --> 03:35:15.080
[Guest]: NPR podcast when that bloody Lehman broke and they started Planet Money. I was addicted

03:35:15.080 --> 03:35:20.120
[Guest]: to that podcast and I haven't missed an episode in the last so many years. And I was like

03:35:20.120 --> 03:35:26.000
[Guest]: podcast. And I think he started out in 2013, 14. I forget when we started a podcast. And

03:35:26.000 --> 03:35:30.920
[Guest]: I was like, why the fuck should I start a podcast? I like do it. It is the most highest

03:35:30.920 --> 03:35:35.880
[Guest]: engagement thing. And sure, it was. And when we put it behind the paywall, you know, that's

03:35:35.880 --> 03:35:40.520
[Guest]: when we saw the biggest spurt in subscribers back then, when we just had three or four

03:35:40.520 --> 03:35:45.200
[Guest]: ground reporters. Today, we have maybe 10, 11, 12 ground reporters. And we want to take

03:35:45.200 --> 03:35:49.760
[Guest]: this number up to 50 ground reporters. We want to have the network of reporters who

03:35:49.760 --> 03:35:54.880
[Guest]: are passionate, driven and not influenced by advertisers.

03:35:54.880 --> 03:36:01.960
[Amit Varma]: Fabulous. But my one comment on that issue about, you know, a handful of these networks

03:36:01.960 --> 03:36:06.640
[Amit Varma]: owning the Internet is that, yes, I think that's an existential threat to all of us.

03:36:06.640 --> 03:36:12.120
[Amit Varma]: And I'm incredibly worried about it. But I also feel that we should not reflexively think

03:36:12.120 --> 03:36:16.360
[Amit Varma]: of state coercion as the answer. If state coercion is to be the answer, then it's people

03:36:16.360 --> 03:36:20.760
[Amit Varma]: like Modi who could be deciding or people like Trump. And so I'm just really wary of

03:36:20.760 --> 03:36:24.560
[Amit Varma]: that. That's fine. You want to regulate the media, but who's regulating you? You know,

03:36:24.560 --> 03:36:29.480
[Amit Varma]: any dispensation that really regulates you through the power of the state will crush

03:36:29.480 --> 03:36:33.460
[Amit Varma]: dissent in some way or the other. That's kind of what I mean. Yeah, that's a more complicated

03:36:33.460 --> 03:36:39.920
[Guest]: discussion that, you know, we can leave for some other day, but there's an inevitability

03:36:39.920 --> 03:36:48.080
[Guest]: to governments. And there's an inevitability to governments framing regulatory frameworks.

03:36:48.080 --> 03:36:50.080
[Guest]: Do you want to influence that as much as possible?

03:36:50.080 --> 03:36:56.640
[Guest]: Yeah. Now, how you go about that is a different, but at least in the current state of how things

03:36:56.640 --> 03:37:00.800
[Guest]: are run in the world, you can't get around that problem. And one thing that I've learned

03:37:00.800 --> 03:37:09.200
[Guest]: from people like Arvind especially is that identify the problem that you can't change

03:37:09.200 --> 03:37:14.480
[Guest]: and then fucking set that aside as a given. This is a given we're living with. Now, what

03:37:14.480 --> 03:37:22.440
[Guest]: can I change to get to where I want to get? Governments framing policy for anything is

03:37:22.440 --> 03:37:32.000
[Guest]: a given. How we get about influencing that is what we can do. Well said, you know, you

03:37:32.000 --> 03:37:35.040
[Amit Varma]: mentioned highway on a plate and all that. I won't ask you to elaborate on it at a too

03:37:35.040 --> 03:37:40.320
[Amit Varma]: much length, but I have a broader question that also kind of touches upon that experience,

03:37:40.320 --> 03:37:45.000
[Amit Varma]: which is that you, you spoke that while shooting highway on a plate, you visited every state

03:37:45.000 --> 03:37:50.760
[Amit Varma]: in this country, which is phenomenal. Now, both of us grew up in little privileged bubbles

03:37:50.760 --> 03:37:55.520
[Amit Varma]: over time. We came out of it little bits at a time and our eyes open and you see something

03:37:55.520 --> 03:37:59.120
[Amit Varma]: new and a layer falls off somewhere and a veil falls off somewhere else. And you see

03:37:59.120 --> 03:38:06.080
[Amit Varma]: something in a way that you didn't see before. And in your case, one as a general thing,

03:38:06.080 --> 03:38:10.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, when you look back as the young you, the 20 year old you, and you look at

03:38:10.600 --> 03:38:16.040
[Amit Varma]: you today, what are the layers that you think fell off? In what way are you kind of different

03:38:16.040 --> 03:38:22.160
[Amit Varma]: from that? And would this experience of having taken you to so many states for this show

03:38:22.160 --> 03:38:27.400
[Amit Varma]: and would also the experience of so much ground reporting, you know, actually, you know, getting

03:38:27.400 --> 03:38:31.900
[Amit Varma]: out in the field and, you know, even though a lot of ground reporting may have been back

03:38:31.900 --> 03:38:36.320
[Amit Varma]: in the day, you know, how did this make you see the country differently? Like if there's

03:38:36.320 --> 03:38:40.120
[Amit Varma]: a young person who, who has the same kind of background as you and I do, but they're

03:38:40.120 --> 03:38:43.640
[Amit Varma]: young, they're 22, what do you want to tell them that, bro, the world is not how you see

03:38:43.640 --> 03:38:49.760
[Guest]: it, but what else would you add to that? I mean, there are many things, but I mean, maybe

03:38:49.760 --> 03:38:55.520
[Guest]: the couple of things that are most important learnings for me were that, you know, I had

03:38:55.520 --> 03:39:03.000
[Guest]: this cockiness and arrogance that, that many people have, because, you know, I come from

03:39:03.000 --> 03:39:07.320
[Guest]: a home that is very well read, I have read so many books, I went to a good school, I

03:39:07.320 --> 03:39:12.880
[Guest]: passed exams fairly effortlessly, I never owned a textbook in my life. And yet I'd,

03:39:12.880 --> 03:39:19.440
[Guest]: you know, I'd pass, I may not top, and people would say, you know, you have that cockiness.

03:39:19.440 --> 03:39:25.080
[Guest]: The one thing that I learned through my travels with having a plate, the documentary films

03:39:25.080 --> 03:39:36.200
[Guest]: I shot, Arvind, everybody, the people who are in the gig, know the gig best. So, which

03:39:36.200 --> 03:39:42.840
[Guest]: is why central planning is something that I'm completely against the whole Swaraj model.

03:39:42.840 --> 03:39:48.080
[Guest]: And I'll illustrate this by one specific example, because while I was shooting having a plate,

03:39:48.080 --> 03:39:53.080
[Guest]: I was also flirting with activism at the time, you know, quote, unquote, again, you called

03:39:53.080 --> 03:39:57.840
[Guest]: yourself a journalist earlier, and you've spoken about that right now. Great. So you're

03:39:57.840 --> 03:40:02.520
[Amit Varma]: exhausting me to submission. This is the whole reason of for our podcast, you tire the person

03:40:02.520 --> 03:40:09.040
[Guest]: out and then they speak the truth. But, you know, we were in the Northeast, I think this

03:40:09.040 --> 03:40:15.680
[Guest]: must have been, maybe somewhere near Nagaland. I think this was in a village called Thembang,

03:40:15.680 --> 03:40:21.920
[Guest]: if I'm not wrong. And, you know, have you traveled to Arunachal Nagaland, etc? No, sadly

03:40:21.920 --> 03:40:26.560
[Guest]: not. It's really, I mean, now, of course, when you go into Arunachal, that you have

03:40:26.560 --> 03:40:29.840
[Guest]: to stop to show your inner line permit, etc. Now there's lots of shops there, where I had

03:40:29.840 --> 03:40:34.760
[Guest]: gone for the first time. It was like, you go then there's this deep green river and

03:40:34.760 --> 03:40:39.200
[Guest]: lush forest, like Jurassic Park, you know, it's a, it's very dramatic entry. And then

03:40:39.200 --> 03:40:43.480
[Guest]: as you go further, because they're clouds very low, now you like driving in and out

03:40:43.480 --> 03:40:50.080
[Guest]: of clouds. It's really, I mean, the visibility can be very low. And the weather isn't that

03:40:50.080 --> 03:40:54.000
[Guest]: great all the time. So, and you know, in the evening, when you're not shooting, you sit

03:40:54.000 --> 03:40:59.680
[Guest]: with whether you're in a village, you go. I was like, what would you want over here

03:40:59.680 --> 03:41:07.840
[Guest]: if you were given the funds in this local area? This is a cinema hall. Someone said

03:41:07.840 --> 03:41:16.000
[Guest]: a hall where we can have marriages, parties, you know, dance parties, music. I was like,

03:41:16.000 --> 03:41:23.120
[Guest]: dude, like, seriously, this is why, you know, central planning may be a good idea. What

03:41:23.120 --> 03:41:29.280
[Guest]: do they want? A cinema hall. They want a hall for parties. And then when you stay and talk,

03:41:29.280 --> 03:41:33.520
[Guest]: you understand why they said, because in our village, if any kid wants to watch a movie

03:41:33.520 --> 03:41:37.320
[Guest]: or wants any entertainment, they have to go to, you know, depending on which village,

03:41:37.320 --> 03:41:43.840
[Guest]: Kohima, Phunishalong. And you've seen the roads here. We lose whatever X amount of kids

03:41:43.840 --> 03:41:48.440
[Guest]: every year to accidents. If they had a place here, they wouldn't drive 40 kilometers away

03:41:48.440 --> 03:41:53.400
[Guest]: to watch a film or to go for a party or to play in a band. There should be one close

03:41:53.400 --> 03:41:58.600
[Guest]: by. And I'm like, you know, would a central planner here saying that, you know, in the

03:41:58.600 --> 03:42:05.080
[Guest]: Northeast, in these eight villages, what should we put? Would anyone say cinema hall? No man.

03:42:05.080 --> 03:42:09.840
[Guest]: Would they say a bloody hall for music system and a stage where people can perform? No.

03:42:09.840 --> 03:42:16.240
[Guest]: They say, Khamba lagao, bamboo lagao, whatever the fuck lagao. No, those guys know best.

03:42:16.240 --> 03:42:22.040
[Guest]: And when you sit and talk to them, you get. So one learning was that. Oh, lovely story,

03:42:22.040 --> 03:42:27.160
[Guest]: which you might like. I know your listeners would have said this on a Highway My Plate

03:42:27.160 --> 03:42:32.800
[Guest]: podcast. There's a place near Rajasthan called Sendra. It has the best dahi bhallas in the

03:42:32.800 --> 03:42:38.800
[Guest]: country. Now, before Pragati Padana was demolished, there used to be an annual food festival there

03:42:38.800 --> 03:42:47.160
[Guest]: and prizes are given that most, you know, best chart. These are winning best dahi bhalla

03:42:47.160 --> 03:42:53.720
[Guest]: for years. So we were supposed to go to Jaipur from Jaipur, you know, via Jaisalmer, ahead

03:42:53.720 --> 03:42:58.040
[Guest]: all that. But we had to make this detour to Sendra for dahi bhallas because our research

03:42:58.040 --> 03:43:01.960
[Guest]: showed that there's this place called Sendra. I was like, dude, we're going to take a hundred

03:43:01.960 --> 03:43:08.320
[Guest]: kilometre detour for dahi bhallas, like one sequence. And as a producer, you're thinking,

03:43:08.320 --> 03:43:11.600
[Guest]: is it worth the trip? So I was in any case in a very negative frame of mind. I was like,

03:43:11.600 --> 03:43:15.760
[Guest]: how special can dahi bhalla be? So while I was sitting there, you know, waiting for the

03:43:15.760 --> 03:43:23.200
[Guest]: shot to be set up, I was telling Rocky, bloody fucking what, two hour detour for dahi bhalla.

03:43:23.200 --> 03:43:29.200
[Guest]: How special can dahi bhalla be? Dahi bhalla is dahi bhalla. The guy heard me. Now you're

03:43:29.200 --> 03:43:34.200
[Guest]: cocky, arrogant, city slicker. Isko angrezi nahi aati hogi. Usko toh saare aati hi thi.

03:43:34.200 --> 03:43:38.280
[Guest]: Although he was dressed in his, you know. He said, aapne kahi yeh scotch whisky baat

03:43:38.280 --> 03:43:43.280
[Guest]: se boor rahe hai? Whisky toh whisky hai. Scotch wali kyu khaas hai? Aur yahan aamari wali

03:43:43.280 --> 03:43:49.200
[Guest]: kyu achi nahi hai? Maine kahi, bataiye. He says, kyunki Scotland ki stream hai ta, uska

03:43:49.200 --> 03:43:54.200
[Guest]: paani khaas hota hai. Unki hawa khaas hoti hai. Wo jin lakdi mein rakhta hai, wo lakdi

03:43:54.200 --> 03:43:59.200
[Guest]: khaas hoti hai. Toh wo taste aapko yahan mili nahi sakta. Hamari jo gai hai, jisse ham

03:43:59.200 --> 03:44:05.200
[Guest]: dood nikalenge, uska jo dahi banta hai. Is hawa mein banta hai. Jo ghaas wo khaati hai.

03:44:05.200 --> 03:44:09.200
[Guest]: Jo ham paani use karte hai. Aap jaante hain, jab aapko Delhi aate hain, Pragati Meydan

03:44:09.200 --> 03:44:13.200
[Guest]: dahi bhalle banane. Ham teen tanker yahan se laate hain, aapke paani se nahi banate

03:44:13.200 --> 03:44:18.200
[Guest]: dahi bhalle ham. Agar scotch whisky khaas hoti hai, dahi bhalla khaas kyu nahi hoti

03:44:18.200 --> 03:44:21.200
[Guest]: hai. Toh nahi hoti hai. I was like, fuck man, that makes sense. He says, aap yahan

03:44:21.200 --> 03:44:24.200
[Guest]: se, main aapko bata doong hain hum kya kya daalte hain, kitna daalte hain. Dil mein

03:44:24.200 --> 03:44:29.200
[Guest]: bana ke dekha doon. Nahi aapke paas hamara paani hai, nahi meri ghaas hai, nahi meri

03:44:29.200 --> 03:44:35.200
[Guest]: ghaas hai. Aap se banega hi nahi. I said, okay, fuck you, Niku. You fucking talk too

03:44:35.200 --> 03:44:39.200
[Amit Varma]: much. Shut the fuck up. You know. How were the dahi bhallas? Outstanding, dude. And

03:44:39.200 --> 03:44:44.200
[Guest]: I'm not a dahi bhalla guy. And I was like, fuck, you're right, man. There is something

03:44:44.200 --> 03:44:51.200
[Guest]: about this which is, I can't get in Delhi. And I mean, other than the film that I want

03:44:51.200 --> 03:44:54.200
[Guest]: to make, one thing that I want to do is, with Rocky, Mayur and Prashant, I want to write

03:44:54.200 --> 03:45:01.200
[Guest]: a book on Highway Unplayed. We have about 12,000 photographs. And Prashant and Rocky

03:45:01.200 --> 03:45:06.200
[Guest]: aap photograph ki raas. They were fucking, I'm an impatient guy when I'm shooting. And

03:45:06.200 --> 03:45:09.200
[Guest]: photographers are impatient. They're saying, wait, abhi aa raha hai, kadik. I said, we

03:45:09.200 --> 03:45:14.200
[Guest]: have to make 500 kilometers today. Ek aur photograph, kadik, kadik. Fuck, they would

03:45:14.200 --> 03:45:21.200
[Guest]: just maro my bund by bloody taking pictures. But now I see why. Because we have got pictures

03:45:21.200 --> 03:45:27.200
[Guest]: from Kashmir to Kanyakumari, from Kutch to fucking Arunachal. Like, I have a big poster

03:45:27.200 --> 03:45:31.200
[Guest]: in my house, which has about 100 pictures, this, this, this, this size. It starts off

03:45:31.200 --> 03:45:35.200
[Guest]: on the left corner with Kashmir, ends with Kanyakumari, and there's every state in the

03:45:35.200 --> 03:45:42.200
[Guest]: front, like from Somnath Temple to Ajmer to bloody Nagaland to Tawang Monastery to Leh.

03:45:42.200 --> 03:45:50.200
[Guest]: That is one mission that I want, that this book has stories of, and I'm not saying this

03:45:50.200 --> 03:45:56.200
[Guest]: in the chest-thumping that I love my India, Subhash Ghai or Akshay Kumar way, but the

03:45:56.200 --> 03:46:02.200
[Guest]: magic that, that being out there does. Probably this will happen to any country, but our country

03:46:02.200 --> 03:46:06.200
[Guest]: is very diverse. I think there's one cliche about India, that is that everything you say

03:46:06.200 --> 03:46:10.200
[Guest]: about India, the opposite is also true. Yeah, exactly. We are extremely kind, we are very

03:46:10.200 --> 03:46:15.200
[Guest]: cruel. What, what Veer Das has just said, which he's got a lot of flack for, he's making

03:46:15.200 --> 03:46:19.200
[Guest]: a different point, but everything I say about India is the opposite, also very true. We

03:46:19.200 --> 03:46:24.200
[Guest]: are extremely cruel and callous because of how we see lynchings happen in front of us.

03:46:24.200 --> 03:46:30.200
[Guest]: Like, in a country which is not considered so civilized as the US, even if a guy who

03:46:30.200 --> 03:46:34.200
[Guest]: looks like me with a beard, brown skin and all, if I'm suffering with someone, I'll be

03:46:34.200 --> 03:46:39.200
[Guest]: like, dude, you okay? Can I help you? Like in Germany, this guy really poached my cab.

03:46:39.200 --> 03:46:42.200
[Guest]: The guys in line said, we're really sorry, Germany is not like this. That guy is not

03:46:42.200 --> 03:46:47.200
[Guest]: from here. And they got me a cab because I was standing in line, the line was behind

03:46:47.200 --> 03:46:52.200
[Guest]: me and some guy just came and took the cab. Would that happen here? No. And we said, we

03:46:52.200 --> 03:47:01.200
[Guest]: are more civilized? No. But yes, here, when, you know, I was unwell, bloody people who

03:47:01.200 --> 03:47:06.200
[Guest]: you can't stand will come and give you blood when, and people who we don't see eye to eye

03:47:06.200 --> 03:47:10.200
[Guest]: to, we fight so much, yeah. Politically, we are on opposite sides. Prashant is, you know,

03:47:10.200 --> 03:47:14.200
[Guest]: Sushant's brother, Sushant sir, you see him on times often. He is as right as they come

03:47:14.200 --> 03:47:19.200
[Guest]: and I remember we used to fight so much. When I needed blood, he was there. He says, dude,

03:47:19.200 --> 03:47:25.200
[Guest]: I'm like 100 kilos, take two liters from me, you know. It's very complicated. And if that

03:47:25.200 --> 03:47:30.200
[Guest]: is something that I want to do, maybe, you know, when I'm, if I live to be 60, 65, maybe

03:47:30.200 --> 03:47:35.200
[Guest]: I'll spend five years finally putting all these pictures together and writing my travels

03:47:35.200 --> 03:47:41.200
[Guest]: and learnings from people like this guy who used to run this small dosa shop between,

03:47:41.200 --> 03:47:46.200
[Guest]: where do all the South Indian chefs come from? What's that? Udipi. Udipi to Mangalore, I

03:47:46.200 --> 03:47:51.200
[Guest]: think that was a stretch. He runs a small dosa shop. He's, he didn't even have two clothes

03:47:51.200 --> 03:47:58.200
[Guest]: to cover his body. We were a crew of 10. We must have eaten like 500 worth of dosa. We

03:47:58.200 --> 03:48:02.200
[Guest]: said, eat, okay. And we had a policy, we'd pay, otherwise we will not review it because

03:48:02.200 --> 03:48:07.200
[Guest]: you can't go eat for free and say that we. So we tell all the dhaba owners, restaurants,

03:48:07.200 --> 03:48:11.200
[Guest]: and then they'd understand, you know, all the hospitality, because after Rocky Mahir

03:48:11.200 --> 03:48:15.200
[Guest]: became big names, people would want to see us review. So we said, and people would say,

03:48:15.200 --> 03:48:20.200
[Guest]: we won't feature you. Then they'd say, okay, fine. Take the money. This guy said, I won't

03:48:20.200 --> 03:48:25.200
[Guest]: take money. I said, dude, you can't not take money. There are fucking 10 of us. Your hole

03:48:25.200 --> 03:48:33.200
[Guest]: in the wall is worth less than one wheel of a car. So please, please, no, no, no, no.

03:48:33.200 --> 03:48:37.200
[Guest]: And you know, there was a language barrier because then I usually pull out my Trump card

03:48:37.200 --> 03:48:39.200
[Guest]: and then we won't feature you on the show because that's our policy. He says, don't

03:48:39.200 --> 03:48:43.200
[Guest]: feature me. He said, I don't want to be featured in your show. It's late at night. You've

03:48:43.200 --> 03:48:48.200
[Guest]: come here. I enjoyed talking to you. I fed you those cells. I'm not going to take money

03:48:48.200 --> 03:48:52.200
[Guest]: from you. If that means you don't feature me, don't feature me. You know, you fucking

03:48:52.200 --> 03:48:56.200
[Guest]: meet magical people who have nothing and will give you everything. So, and you can't cross

03:48:56.200 --> 03:49:01.200
[Amit Varma]: dicks also. So yeah, someday. Yeah. I mean, that cliche is one. In fact, I keep repeating

03:49:01.200 --> 03:49:05.200
[Amit Varma]: about the opposite also being true in India. I'd done an episode with JP Narayan where

03:49:05.200 --> 03:49:11.200
[Amit Varma]: I put to him, I mentioned what an illiberal society India had. And of course I meant things

03:49:11.200 --> 03:49:15.200
[Amit Varma]: like how we treat women, caste, all of that. And he said at the same time, it's very liberal

03:49:15.200 --> 03:49:18.200
[Amit Varma]: in some ways. You look at the cuisine, look at the food, which you ate. Everything in

03:49:18.200 --> 03:49:23.200
[Amit Varma]: every meal you must have eaten has really come from all over the place. And just to

03:49:23.200 --> 03:49:29.200
[Amit Varma]: add something to this Dahi Valla angle, one angle he probably forgot is that, for example,

03:49:29.200 --> 03:49:35.200
[Amit Varma]: why do people eat so much tomato juice when they're flying? Because at that altitude,

03:49:35.200 --> 03:49:41.200
[Amit Varma]: it doesn't taste but taste and tomato juice, tomato juice tastes better for that way, which

03:49:41.200 --> 03:49:44.200
[Amit Varma]: is why they sell more of it up there than down here. So maybe there's something to that

03:49:44.200 --> 03:49:49.200
[Amit Varma]: as well. And yeah, and I, of course, you know, as you would know, I have a deep distaste

03:49:49.200 --> 03:49:55.200
[Amit Varma]: for central planning, but that is one way in which Modiji and Heruji are exactly the

03:49:55.200 --> 03:50:00.200
[Amit Varma]: same, great belief in doing everything from the top down. So I'm, you know, I've really

